    <subsection xml:id="ON2-subsec-class-activities">
        <title>Class Activities</title>

        <fact xml:id="fact-ortho-decomp-thm">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>W</m> be a subspace of <m>\IR^n</m> and let <m>\vec u</m> be a vector in <m>\IR^n</m>.
                    Then we can write <m>\vec u</m> uniquely as
                    <me>\vec u=\vec u_W+\vec u_{W^\perp}</me>
                    where <m>\vec u_W</m> is the closest vector to <m>\vec u</m> on <m>W</m> and <m>\vec u_{W^\perp}</m> is in <m>W^\perp</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </fact>

        <definition xml:id="def-orthogonal-decompostion">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>W</m> be a subspace of <m>\IR^n</m> and let <m>\vec u</m> be a vector in <m>\IR^n</m>.
                    The <term>orthogonal decompostion </term> of <m>\vec u</m> is the decomposition of <m>\vec u</m> given by 
                    <xref ref="fact-ortho-decomp-thm"/>. The <term>orthogonal projection</term> of <m>\vec u</m> is <m>\vec u_W</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <activity>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    Let <m>W</m> be a the <m>xy</m>-plane in <m>\IR^2</m>. 
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        have them find a simple orthogonal decomposition
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </activity>

        <fact>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>T:\IR^n\rightarrow\IR^m</m> be a linear transformation with standard matrix <m>A</m>.
                    Let <m>W</m> be the image of <m>T</m>, that is, <m>W</m> is spanned by the columns of <m>A</m>.
                    Then for any <m>\vec u</m> in <m>\IR^m</m>, the matrix equation 
                    <me>
                        A^TA\vec x=A^T\vec u
                    </me>
                    is consistent, and <m>\vec u_W=A\vec x</m> for any solution <m>\vec x</m>.
                    
                </p>
            </statement>
        </fact>

        <!-- <p>
            Insert scaffolded activity that has them compute both sides of the equation from the above fact for a given standard matrix <m>A</m> with one column and a given vector <m>\vec u</m>. Finally,
            they will solve for <m>\vec x</m> to see the following observation.
        </p> -->

        <observation>
        When the image of a linear transformation is one-dimensional, then its standard matrix <m>A</m> only has one column <m>\vec c</m>,
        and for any vector <m>\vec u</m>,
        <me>
            \vec u_W=\dfrac{\vec u\cdot \vec c}{\vec c\cdot \vec c}\vec c.
        </me>
        </observation>

    </subsection>


